<span id="freeTextContainer6864214099057226676">To put it simply, I really liked this book. From the writer&apos;s style and wit to the information conveyed, this is your typical &quot;can&apos;t put down&quot; book. For those of you who aren&apos;t quite convinced that &quot;global warming&quot; is THE greatest threat to life as we know it, this book is for you. The author&apos;s coverage of topics, including how demographics and Europe&apos;s general lack of Christian religion has allowed for major changes to take place in many European countries (one of my favorite quotes from the bo</span>
  <span id="freeText6864214099057226676" style="display:none">To put it simply, I really liked this book. From the writer's style and wit to the information conveyed, this is your typical "can't put down" book. For those of you who aren't quite convinced that "global warming" is THE greatest threat to life as we know it, this book is for you. The author's coverage of topics, including how demographics and Europe's general lack of Christian religion has allowed for major changes to take place in many European countries (one of my favorite quotes from the book comes to mind: when religion is marginalized, only the marginalized have religion). Fundalmentalism in any form is dangerous. It especially becomes dangerous when those fundalmentalists think you should convert or be killed. For me, I think Islamo-fascism poses a greater threat to our way of life than the hypothesis called "global warming." Just a thought. <br /><br />This book is very smartly written, and is not an emotional rant. He has done his homework and knows his topic well. </span>
